<article class="judah" id="main">

  <header class="masthead">
    <p class="wordmark">Work with me</p>
    <p class="by">Lee Wilkers</p>
  </header>

  <p>I&rsquo;ve specialized in being a generalist. That means I don&rsquo;t sell you fancy frameworks or design fads. What I can do, again and again, is help you think clearly about hard institutional problems.</p>

  <p>The useful frames usually come from outside the field where the institution sits (e.g., organizational sociology, decision theory, design research, theories of measurement and scaling, and many others). My job is bringing those frames to your problem.</p>

  <p>I work mostly with teams who are mid-strategy or mid-program when it becomes clear no one has said what the real problem is yet. I&rsquo;m a trained qualitative researcher &mdash; that means a lot of listening carefully, reading carefully, and noticing the gap between what&rsquo;s said and what&rsquo;s happening. Most of my work to date has been in global health and institutional research.</p>

  <hr>

  <p><strong>Where I tend to be useful.</strong></p>

  <ol class="judah-aka-list">
    <li>A formal process everyone attends and nobody uses to make the decisions it governs. The real decision room is somewhere else, and everyone in the building can tell you where.
      <span class="aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decoupling" rel="noopener">decoupling</a><span class="gwern-note"><span class="gwern-note-marker" tabindex="0">&sup1;</span><span class="gwern-note-popover"><span class="np-gloss">Organizations adopt formal structures for legitimacy while loosely coupling them from the actual technical work. What gets done is decoupled from what the formal structure promises.</span></span></span> (Meyer &amp; Rowan, 1977).</span>
    </li>
    <li>Every actor can explain procedurally why the failure was someone else&rsquo;s piece. The frontline carries the consequence; nobody owns the whole.
      <span class="aka">AKA the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Problem_of_many_hands" rel="noopener">problem of many hands</a><span class="gwern-note"><span class="gwern-note-marker" tabindex="0">&sup2;</span><span class="gwern-note-popover"><span class="np-gloss">When many actors contribute to an outcome, no single person can be held responsible. Accountability dissipates across the contributors and the harm has no clear owner.</span></span></span> (Thompson, 1980).</span>
    </li>
    <li>An indicator that improves every quarter while the encounter, outcome, or relationship it was supposed to protect is not. Nobody in the room can say so without sounding like they&rsquo;re against measurement.
      <span class="aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodhart%27s_law" rel="noopener">Goodhart&rsquo;s law</a><span class="gwern-note"><span class="gwern-note-marker" tabindex="0">&sup3;</span><span class="gwern-note-popover"><span class="np-gloss">When a measure becomes a target, it ceases to be a good measure. Gaming the indicator displaces the work the indicator was meant to capture.</span></span></span> (1975).</span>
    </li>
    <li>A funded vertical everyone (including the funder) knows shouldn&rsquo;t exist standalone, kept alive because folding it in would force someone to be first to write off the past commitment.
      <span class="aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Escalation_of_commitment" rel="noopener">escalation of commitment</a><span class="gwern-note"><span class="gwern-note-marker" tabindex="0">&#8308;</span><span class="gwern-note-popover"><span class="np-gloss">Continuing to invest in a failing course of action because of prior commitments, rather than evaluating future prospects on their own merits. Sunk-cost reasoning at the organizational scale.</span></span></span> (Staw, 1976).</span>
    </li>
    <li>A leader who has to say something publicly that&rsquo;s defensible, when the technically honest version sounds weaker than what the moment allows.
      <span class="aka">AKA <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strategic_ambiguity" rel="noopener">strategic ambiguity</a><span class="gwern-note"><span class="gwern-note-marker" tabindex="0">&#8309;</span><span class="gwern-note-popover"><span class="np-gloss">Deliberately vague communication that lets multiple audiences read different meanings into the same words. Preserves room to maneuver, at the cost of being honest with any one of them.</span></span></span> (Eisenberg, 1984).</span>
    </li>
    <li>A team whose program becomes fragile the moment one person is unavailable, because the work that held it together was never written down.
      <span class="aka">AKA the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bus_factor" rel="noopener">bus factor</a><span class="gwern-note"><span class="gwern-note-marker" tabindex="0">&#8310;</span><span class="gwern-note-popover"><span class="np-gloss">The number of people whose unexpected absence would cripple a project, because they hold critical undocumented knowledge. Low bus factor = fragile institution.</span></span></span>.</span>
    </li>
  </ol>

  <hr>

  <p><strong>Getting started.</strong> If you&rsquo;d like to work together, send me a short or long note about the problem you&rsquo;re working on. I&rsquo;ll ask a few follow-up questions to figure out whether I can be useful before either of us puts time or money down. The more context you share, the better I can prepare. I usually reply within a few days; first calls typically happen within a week or two.</p>

  <p>If you&rsquo;d like to read more before our first call, <a href="/consider-the-tree/">Consider the tree</a> is the longer written version of how I work.</p>

  <hr>

  <p><strong>Working with me.</strong> Most engagements start with a paid thought-sparring conversation: <strong>$350 for a 60&ndash;90 minute call</strong>. I send a few prep questions a day or two ahead. The call is where I work out whether I can be useful to your problem, and where you work out whether you want to keep going.</p>

  <p>Within a few days after the call, you get a short written follow-up: what I would actually do, what I would want to know more about, and whether I think I am a fit. If we keep going, we agree scope and rate in writing &mdash; usually a fixed-fee deliverable or an hourly block, your preference.</p>

  <p>If $350 is too much, write anyway. Rate flexes for early-stage or public-interest work. I usually have capacity for one or two new engagements at a time.</p>

  <hr>

  <p><strong>Deliverables.</strong> Not every engagement ends in a deliverable. When there is one, it usually takes one of these shapes:</p>

  <ul class="judah-bullets">
    <li>Synthesis memos (5&ndash;15 pages) on a question your team can&rsquo;t get clean on &mdash; <em>Do we have evidence of impact, or not? Did the donor actually sign off on that scope change, or did we assume? Was this CQI or a study?</em> &mdash; usually after several meetings that haven&rsquo;t converged.</li>
    <li>Program audits. What&rsquo;s working, what&rsquo;s reported as working, where the two diverge. Confidential.</li>
    <li>Problem-framing memos for grant proposals, before the drafting starts. Most proposals that fail in writing failed in framing two weeks earlier.</li>
    <li>Workshop facilitation when a team has been circling the same disagreement across multiple meetings.</li>
    <li>Draft text. Policy, IRB, protocol, manuscript framing, board memos. I produce the first draft; you take it from there.</li>
  </ul>

  <hr>

  <p><strong>Contact.</strong> <a href="mailto:lee@leewilkers.com?subject=Consulting%20inquiry">lee@leewilkers.com</a></p>

</article>

<script>
  // Tap-to-toggle for .gwern-note popovers. Hover and keyboard focus stay
  // in CSS; this adds sticky tap-to-open for touch + pin for mouse.
  // Outside-tap dismisses. Auto-right-anchors when marker is past viewport
  // midline so the popover stays on-screen on narrow viewports.
  (function () {
    document.addEventListener('click', function (e) {
      var marker = e.target.closest('.gwern-note-marker');
      if (marker) {
        var note = marker.closest('.gwern-note');
        if (!note) return;
        var wasOpen = note.classList.contains('gwern-note--open');
        document.querySelectorAll('.gwern-note--open').forEach(function (n) {
          n.classList.remove('gwern-note--open');
          n.classList.remove('gwern-note--right');
        });
        if (!wasOpen) {
          var markerRect = marker.getBoundingClientRect();
          if (markerRect.left > window.innerWidth / 2) {
            note.classList.add('gwern-note--right');
          }
          note.classList.add('gwern-note--open');
        }
        e.stopPropagation();
        return;
      }
      if (!e.target.closest('.gwern-note-popover')) {
        document.querySelectorAll('.gwern-note--open').forEach(function (n) {
          n.classList.remove('gwern-note--open');
        });
      }
    });
  })();
</script>
